<div type="a">
<column>1</column>
<head>The Government and the Administration</head>
<origin></origin>
<commentary></commentary>
<transcript>"But some will say that we are weakening the Government by thus criticizing the acts
of the administration. No.  We will strengthen it, by bringing it back within the citadel of the
Constitution, where it can withstand the attacks of its foes for ages."</transcript>
<trailer></trailer>
<names></names>
<summary>The most dangerous assumption of the party in power, say the editors, is that there is
no difference between the government and the administration. Thus, criticism of the
administration is interpreted as criticism of the government, and thus is seen as disloyal and
subject to restraint when habeas corpus is suspended. The editors then discuss the differences
between a government and an administration.  They claim that their criticism of the administration
actually strengthens, not weakens, the country, for it helps keep the administration's power
bounded by the Constitution.</summary>
<note></note>
<look></look>
</div>

<div type="a">
<column>2</column>
<head></head>
<origin></origin>
<commentary></commentary>
<transcript>"Really, this ignorance in inexcusable in the editor of a political
newspaper."</transcript>
<trailer></trailer>
<names></names>
<summary>The editors attack an editorial in the Repository and Transcript that accused the
Democrats, when in power, of plunder and robbery. The Spirit and Times argues that the
Repository's editor must have slept through the past two years and missed the cases of George
D. Morgan, Senators Chandler and Cummings, Assistant Secretary of War Tucker, and Governor
Curtain, all Republicans accused of swindling or nepotism.</summary>
<note></note>
<look></look>
</div>

<div type="a">
<column>3</column>
<head></head>
<origin>New York Herald</origin>
<commentary></commentary>
<transcript>"Now if the slaves of the rebels should be freed, why not free the wives of the
rebels?"</transcript>
<trailer></trailer>
<names></names>
<summary>Since the Emancipation Proclamation has failed to free the slaves of the South, says
the writer sarcastically, a new tactic should be tried--pass a proclamation divorcing all the
women of the South from their husbands. They give more aid and comfort to the rebels than the
slaves, after all.</summary>
<note></note>
<look></look>
</div>

<div type="a">
<column>3</column>
<head></head>
<origin></origin>
<commentary></commentary>
<transcript></transcript>
<trailer></trailer>
<names></names>
<summary>The editors publish a claim by the Repository and Transcript that General McClellan
is a member of the Knights of the Golden Circle, a secret Democratic military society. Either
provide proof of the claim, they demand, or retract the slander against McClellan.</summary>
<note></note>
<look></look>
</div>

<div type="a">
<column>3</column>
<head>Railroad Accident</head>
<origin></origin>
<commentary></commentary>
<transcript></transcript>
<trailer></trailer>
<names>
<name><ln>Laker</ln><fn>John H.</fn><sf></sf><pf></pf></name>
</names>
<summary>John H. Laker of Quincy Township was hit by the afternoon train from Hagerstown
last Saturday while he was driving his wagon over the "Waynesboro Cut" across the railroad
tracks. He and his horse escaped without harm, but his wagon was destroyed. A public meeting
held shortly thereafter in Quincy resolved to petition the legislature to pass a law forcing the
railroad company to bridge the cut.</summary>
<note></note>
<look></look>
</div>

